    "analysis": "The previous Executor run computed global P95 thresholds per component-KPI (using full series) and then inspected the incident window. Top per-KPI metric breaches (by breach_count and breach_ratio) included payment.cpu (highest relative exceedance), carts.cpu, orders.latency-90, payment.latency-90 and queue-master.diskio. Aggregating breaches by service, 'orders' had the largest total breach count (14), followed by front-end (13), carts (12), catalogue (12), payment (12), shipping (11), and user (10). Log analysis showed elevated log.row_count for front-end and orders (each with breach_count=2), and several other services with 1–2 breaches. trace.csv and error_logs.csv are empty. From these results we narrowed candidates to service-level faults across multiple services; without traces we must rely on metrics and logs to localize the root cause. Orders stands out as the most impacted service (highest aggregate breach count) and also shows multi-KPI anomalies (cpu, latency, socket, error), plus log.row_count breaches. However, payment.cpu shows the single largest relative exceedance vs P95. To decide whether 'orders' is the root cause or another service (e.g., payment), we need to verify whether the anomalies for the candidate services are consecutive (forming faults) and determine the fault start times (earliest breach timestamps) and severity (max values). This will allow us to pick the most plausible root-cause service and associated reason (resource) following the fault identification and root localization rules.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Focus on the candidate services 'orders' and 'payment'. Using metric.csv and log.csv, recompute full-series P95 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) as before, then filter to the incident window 2024-01-20 17:50:28–2024-01-20 18:20:28 UTC. For each of these two services, and for KPIs: cpu, latency-90, latency-50, socket, error (only if present), do the following and return compact tables:\n1) For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name): list breach timestamps in the window where value > full-series P95 (as Unix seconds), breach_count, whether the breaches form a consecutive run (True/False), earliest_breach_timestamp (unix seconds or NaN), last_breach_timestamp (unix seconds or NaN), max_value_in_window, p95_threshold, and breach_ratio = (max_value_in_window - p95_threshold)/p95_threshold (NaN if no breach). Limit output to these rows (one per KPI).\n2) For 'orders' also return log.csv rows within the window for cmdb_id='orders' and log_name in [log.row_count, log.error_count] with columns (timestamp, log_name, value), plus the full-series P95 for those log_name (so we can compare).\nKeep outputs compact. If a KPI is not present for a service, indicate it as missing. Do not return full time series—only the breach timestamps list and the aggregated fields above." }

